This doesn't work in dotless at the moment. 

Here is my test case..

```
.mixin-arguments3 (@a: 1, @b: @a) {
    test: @a @b;
}
.arguments5 {
    .mixin-arguments3();
    .mixin-arguments3(2);
    .mixin-arguments3(@a:3);
    .mixin-arguments3(@b:3);
}

.arguments5 {
    test: 1 1;
    test: 2 2;
    test: 3 3;
    test: 1 3;
}
```

To implement mixin.Definition.evalParams would have to create a new frame that includes previous arguments. arguments would have to be eval'd as they go along.

Where would that frame go? e.g.

```
@global: 2; 
.mixin-arguments4(@global: 1, @a: @global) {
}
```

which global should it prefer?

could be done but it would be a bit messy and I can't see massive demand, so leaving for now.

:+1:  for implementing this. I used this feature quite a bit in Sass, and I got here because I can't quite figure out how to port my stylesheets.

@evadne explains a good use case for default parameters. https://github.com/cloudhead/less.js/issues/43#issuecomment-283831

@agatronic the implementation you mention does seem heavy-handed, but it has the added benefit of supporting functions as default values. I've been using those a lot in Sass. I define mixins that cover entire widgets (e.g. a text field), default all the colors (font, borders, shadows in all states) based on one color, and allow keyword arguments to override the auto-generated colors.

In case it helps, here is the test case I wrote before I started looking at the source code, and realizing this is hard.

``` less
.simple(@color: #ff0000) {
  background-color: @color;
}
.red-button {
  .simple();
}

.chained(@background: #ff0000, @border: @background) {
  background-color: @background;
  border-color: @border;
}
.redder-button {
  .chained();
}

.function(@background: #ff0000, @border: darken(@background, 50%)) {
  background-color: @background;
  border-color: @border;
}
.reddish-button {
  .function();
}
```

And this is the expected result.

``` css
.red-button {
  background-color: #ff0000;
}
.redder-button {
  background-color: #ff0000;
  border-color: #ff0000;
}
.reddish-button {
  background-color: #ff0000;
  border-color: #800000;
}
```
